node.text:
Commissioned by Apple. A peek behind the scenes as Michel Gondry turns a carton of eggs into a dozen pieces of cinema with #iPhone13Pro 🥚 “I like to start with something very trivial and mundane, and find a way to get magic out of it.” #ShotoniPhone by Michel Gondry. @michelgondry

Follow @apple to see more.

Commissioned by Apple. One missing painting. Six Suspects. Watch Whodunnit, shot entirely in Cinematic mode on the new #iPhone13.

#ShotoniPhone by JB Braud @jbbraud

node.title: Shot on iPhone 13 in Cinematic mode

node.text: Commissioned by Apple. “I came up with the idea for my film in a nightmare. I always get my ideas from nightmares. It sounds a bit grim, but it’s not. I just think about what could be happening in a different universe.” #ShotoniPhone by AhaNah C. @vio.waxdrops, Student.

Commissioned by Apple. “I want to see a joyful piece with black men in it because we’re seeing way too much pain in the media and the news. I wanted to create something that would be a much-needed pause from everything that’s happening. I want joy.” #ShotoniPhone by Ciara Z. @ciara.zo, Student.

node.title: Our Light Shines Through the Dark

node.text: Commissioned by Apple. “Making this film was a fantastic feeling. I don’t care about anything else in the world. This is what I want to do.” #ShotoniPhone by Guillermo M., Student.

Commissioned by Apple. “There’s no excuse for anybody not to be making films at this point. It’s a way people can tell their stories and keep them living forever.” #ShotoniPhone by Niko B. @mylifeismundane, Student.

Commissioned by Apple. “We wanted to push the #iPhone12Pro with its Dolby Vision and low-light recording capabilities to the limit.”

#ShotoniPhone 12 Pro by Donghoon J. and James T. of @InciteDesign. 

Music: “RADIANCE” by LORN. 

Head to Stories to see how it was made.

“The unfinished work of racial justice and equality call us all to account. Things must change, and Apple's committed to being a force for that change. Today, I'm proud to announce Apple’s Racial Equity and Justice Initiative, with a $100 million commitment.” Tim Cook

node.title: Apple is taking action to fight systemic racism.

node.text: Commissioned by Apple. Photographer Petecia Le Fawnhawk @Lefawnhawk is known for creating striking surrealist landscapes using a mix of sculpture and editing techniques. Watch to learn about Petecia's creative connection with the desert and how she uses perspective to explore her sense of place in the world. #IWD #ShotoniPhone 11 Pro.

Commissioned by Apple. Fifty miles from Las Vegas, Nevada rests the remains of a prehistoric geological event. Carved by 200 million years of wind. An ocean of rock, a Valley of Fire. 
See how iPhone 11 Pro captured otherworldly imagery using the Ultra Wide camera in this deep dive into another world. 
#ultrawide #ShotoniPhone 11 Pro by Tyler F. @tylerfairbank
Music: “Frontier” by @holly_herndon

Commissioned by Apple. "I walk on the beach every day looking for things to photograph. You get to know the rocks. You have you almost a relationship with your space. And when you change perspective in a way you’re changing the nature of the relationship. And that’s super interesting to me.” #ShotoniPhone by Paul M. @paulmacphail and Scottie C. @scottie_cameron 
Music: “The Immense Endless Belt of Faces” by @elikeszler and “Eighteenth” by @correcreative

Commissioned by Apple. Follow pro snowboarders Red Gerard @redgerard, Danny Davis @travelindan, Kimmy Fasani @kimmyfasani, and Ben Ferguson @ben_ferguson as they explore untouched powder in the backcountry of Interior British Columbia at the legendary Baldface Lodge. #ShotoniPhone by Joe C. @carlinojoevideo
“A certain amount of darkness always helps accentuate a source of light and make it a central part of the scene.” #ShotoniPhone by Tlektes S. @t1lektes
“I love creative shadow play photography because it helps take my perspective and thoughts to the next level.” #ShotoniPhone by Rashid B. @rashid_bin__

“This place is called Seven Sisters because of the seven hilltops that make the silhouette. It’s a unique landscape where the waves hit the cliffs and make a mesmerizing sound. I tried to walk every possible point of it and take as many pictures as I could to do it justice." #ShotoniPhone by Salman A. @salmaninho

node.text:
Commissioned by Apple. As Told By Us: Honoring Pride’s past, present and future through the historic places that started the celebration. Five artists. Five locations. Location #5—Stonewall Inn, New York City.

“Stonewall is a bar, but for most of us, it’s a lifestyle. Stonewall is a state of mind. It’s a home base; an outlet. Stonewall belongs to the people. It represents liberation and soul searching. It’s going against the grain of society and making your own rules. Stonewall is about what you stand for and who you stand with.”
#Pride #ShotoniPhone by Ryan McGinley @ryanmcginleystudios 
-
1. Neptunite describes themselves as “the divine androgynous” and “a sunfire pisces”. Neptunite is a singer and activist, they are pictured here dancing under the tin ceiling of The Stonewall Inn. 
-
2. Lexii Fox is an artist, activist, model, and the founder of a social justice campaign, which seeks to support Black transwomxn. 
-
3. Ramie is a photographer, activist, and student from New Jersey, and currently lives in New York City. Ramie works closely with the Stonewall protests and is pictured sitting on top of the street sign in front of The Stonewall National Monument. 
-
4. This group of people met protesting in front of The Stonewall Inn, in June of 2020, and they have continued doing activism daily.

node.text: “I used the puddles for reflections and the lines to draw attention to the subject. For me, the black and white gives it a more timeless feel and makes the image simpler." #ShotoniPhone by Laurence B. @laurence__bouchard

“I was halfway through my run along the coast in Sydney, and I stopped to catch my breath and watch the surfers. There had been a volcanic eruption in Tonga only a few days earlier, which was one of the reasons the colors were so brilliant. The ash from that eruption made its way to the east coast of Australia, and when combined with the light during golden hour, it made for some spectacular scenes." #ShotoniPhone by Edward R. @eddrobertson
“I saw this person riding their bike from far off. The vibrant red background and colors of the rider really caught my eye." #ShotoniPhone by Uzair Z. @uzairgraphy

Commissioned by Apple. As Told By Us: Five artists honor Pride’s past, present and future by commemorating five global locations and historical events. Location #4 — Paulista Avenue, Sao Paulo.

“I believe that this work honors Pride because it talks about the possibility of occupying spaces that I didn't grow up seeing as possible. Spaces of affection, great achievements, and representation.” #Pride #ShotoniPhone by Caia Ramalho @caiaramalho

Music: “Hi-Fidelity” by @lavalarue feat. @biig_piig

node.text:
Commissioned by Apple. As Told By Us: Honoring Pride’s past, present and future through the historic places that started the celebration. Five artists. Five locations. Location #4 — Paulista Avenue, Sao Paulo.

“Paulista Avenue is important for Brazil because it represents something huge to the LGBTQ+ community, by celebrating the biggest Pride parade in the world, celebrating and also protesting for rights.” #Pride #ShotoniPhone by Caia Ramalho @caiaramalho 
-
1. This video shows the importance of my friends and cycling in my life, the bike to me represents a way of finding independence and freedom.
-
2. Caia riding her bike on Paulista Avenue in the morning.
-
3. Caia on a bike with wind in her hair in front of a backdrop that reminds her of the morning sky and all of the different color palettes that the sun creates.

Commissioned by Apple. As Told By Us: Honoring Pride’s past, present and future through the historic places that started the celebration. Five artists. Five locations. Location #3 — The Homomonument, Amsterdam. 

“With the monument reacting to the past, it felt obvious and important to make this project about the now. We wanted to photograph people of the queer community today. For us, this means friends, and friends-of-friends who we really find inspiring and wanted to spend the day with.” #Pride #ShotoniPhone by Meinke Klein @meinkeklein 
- 
1. This is Felie and Jackie who celebrate queer love publicly as a means of protest, to reclaim their space and voices within society. 
- 
2. Closeup of Felie and Jackie who gratefully thank those who paved the way to make it possible to celebrate queer love in Pride month as loud as we can today. 
- 
3. Alida and Vivian pictured here think Pride feels like the start of summer, being present and content, able to celebrate while knowing better days are yet to come.

“I was walking my dog in mid January and decided to walk around these corn fields. As we walked, I noticed someone up ahead and liked the composition, so I managed to quickly take the photo. The curve of the path leading to the tree helps make for a naturally beautiful photo." #ShotoniPhone by Alan R. @alanincornwall

Commissioned by Apple. As Told By Us: Honoring Pride’s past, present and future through the historic places that started the celebration. Five artists. Five locations. Location #2 — Plaza de Chueca, Madrid.

“This piece of work is a tribute to a very historical place that has helped the queer community get more rights and be recognized. It is important to remember all those who have helped us be privileged, who have fought for our rights. It is also a tribute to our present community—to tell them that they are not alone; we are everywhere, and we are united. We are beautiful and powerful.” #Pride #ShotoniPhone by Lydia M. @lydiametral 
-
1. Adrian is a multidisciplinary artist who has found many opportunities in the city of Madrid and has built strong friendships there. He is now thriving and he is a restless soul who always needs to be creating and experimenting. 
-
2. Lolita Watson and Claret Castell met in 2016 during a photoshoot. They fell in love and got married in 2020 in Madrid and the city has always been an example of tolerance and opportunities for them. Claret remembers feeling very intimidated by Lolita's deep and intense gaze.
-
3. Michelle Nicholas is a trans woman born in La Havana who has discovered herself through dance and theatre. For her, Chueca has always represented freedom. Shehas never felt as safe as she does in this neighborhood, walking through the streets, feeling confident in who she is. 
-
4. Alex was born in Madrid and educated in England. He started working on stage through magic and later became interested in acting, dramaturgy and movement. He has been involved in numerous feminist and queer projects.
